I find his style to be a little offputting. I appreciate the detail and effort, but I can't shake the uncanny feeling on most of his work. That jay is actually better than usual, but the roo gives me the creeps.

>>30203241
Birds are sleek, light, and very purpose built. They're probably the most functionally designed animals. I want to see some of that in the character. The beak, eyes and rest of the head is very important, but most artists do get this right even if nothing else. Boobs are fine and can be great, but they have to be tidy with the body. The ones in pic related are a little too big, but this could be remedied by adding more plumage to give an aerodynamic look. That's something I see rarely, keeping the frame lithe, but adding the appearance of bulk with feathers. It's what real birds do!
Wings can be either way, as long as they're there. I think feather fingers are lazy though. Add a knuckle claw if you want hands integrated on the wing. If you can't get it right, well there's nothing wrong with having the separate arms. Legs and claws are very important. I prefer the "reverse knee" which is actually an ankle, with the true knee tucked up high. I can tell the artist of pic doesn't understand how that all works even though the leg is covered. Minor knit picks, but they add up. I'm probably just picky about birds since they're a favorite of mine. It's depressing to see designs with little thought put in.
